&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Conclusion I:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; No spider is a molar &amp;rarr; False (This is definitely false)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Conclusion II: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;Some spiders are molars &amp;rarr; False (This is possible but not definite)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;   background-color:  (255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Explanation:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0px 0px 10px;   background-color:  (255, 255, 255);&quot;&gt;In the given question, the keywords provided (&lt;em style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Some&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;em style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;box-sizing: border-box; font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;no&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;)&amp;nbsp;satisfy the concept of the Either-or case.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Conclusion I and Conclusion II form a complementary pair.&lt;/p&gt;
Hence,&lt;strong&gt; &amp;ldquo;either conclusion I or conclusion II&amp;rdquo;&lt;/strong&gt; follows.

